\begin_layout Section
Odour representation become concentration invariant in the early stages
 of olfactory processes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flies detect odours using appoximately 1,200 olfactory receptor neurons
 (ORNs) housed in their antennae.
 The tuning of each ORN is determined by a single odorant receptor gene,
 which controls whether the ORN is broadly or narrowly tuned to odours (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Hallem:2006iu"

\end_inset

).
 Axons from the ORN expressing the same receptor always converge on the
 same gomerulus.
 Their activity is picked up by inhibitory and excitatory projection neurons
 which perform normalization of the odour ( 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Luo:2010fb"

\end_inset

).
 Excitatory projection neurons deliver information to the calyces in the
 mushroom body while both inhibitory projection neurons and ePNs send informatio
n to the Lateral Horn.
 The lateral horn is associated with innate behavioral responses to odors,
 such as sex-specific responses to pheromones during courtship (Datta et
 al 2008), whereas the mushroom body is required for learned responses to
 odors (de Belle and Heisenberg, 1994).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The MB is the centre for associative learning in the fruit fly
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mushroom bodies are symmetrical structures with each mushroom body being
 composed of approximately 2,000 Kenyon Cells (KCs) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Turner:2008eo"

\end_inset

).
 Lesion experiments and synaptic blocking of mushroom bodies output have
 shown that that the mushroom body plays a critical role in memory formation
 and retrieval (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Heisenberg:2009bu"

\end_inset

).
 Experimental studies have shown that the MB maintains a sparse representation
 of odours as each odour activates 8% of KCs (approximately 150 neurons)
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Honegger:2011ja"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Similar odours have overlapping representations in the MB
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous experimental studies have shown that odours with similar chemical
 properties have overlapping representations in the MBs ( 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Campbell:2013fb"

\end_inset

 ).
 Behavioural experiments have shown flies have the ability to both generalize
 similar odours and separate them depending on the training protocol.
 If we use a first odour as a CS+ and train the fly to remember it as predicting
 reward the fly will showcase the same behaviour when exposed for the first
 time to a similar odour.
 However if the second odour is shown to the fly in the training odour as
 the neutral odour in the learning paradigm than the fly will not show preferenc
e to it when compared to another neutral odour ( 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Campbell:2013fb"

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The MB recurrent activity is critical for stabilizing odour memories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental studies have shown that olfactory representations in the mushroom
 bodies are modulated by anterior paired lateral (APL) and dorsal paired
 medial (DPM) neurons (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Krashes:2007fh"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Lin:2014io"

\end_inset

).
 The gap-junctional connection between DPM and APL appear to guarantee that
 excitation from DPM is balanced by a similar magnitude of inhibition from
 APL (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Pitman:2011ka"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Anatomical subdivisions of the MB have unique role in odour processing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dendrites of the KCs form the calyx of the MB, and their axons project
 anteriorly to form the peduncle before those axons terminate in one or
 more lobes, termed 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha',\beta'$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe (Fig.1) (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Krashes:2007fh"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 contains 800 KCs while the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha',\beta'$
\end_inset

 contains 600 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe 400 of KCs and each subdivision is believed to have unique roles in
 memory processing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a previous study it has been shown by blocking different anatomical subdivisi
ons of KCs, that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\beta$
\end_inset

 neurons are needed during retrieval of aversive and appetitive memory whereas
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'\beta'$
\end_inset

 core neurons, when blocked only affect appetitive memory (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Perisse:2013fp"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

