\begin_layout Subsection
MBONs guide approach and retreat behaviours
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Outputs from approximately 2,000 Kenyon cells of the mushroom body converge
 onto a population of 34 mushroom body output neurons (MBONs) .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MBON dendrites divide the two lobes and the base of the pedunculus into
 a small number of serial, nonoverlapping compartments, within which the
 dendrite densely contacts either all KCs or an anatomically distinct subpopulat
ion (KC axons in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

/
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 lobes are clustered into anterior, middle, and posterior groups, in the
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

/
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'$
\end_inset

 lobes into posterior, surface, and core groups, and in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe into main and dorsal groups.) The MBONs innervating each compartment
 are genetically distinct, and each projects characteristically to other
 regions of the brain.
 MBONs project from the mushroom body to several regions.
 A small number of excitatory neurons innervating the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 lobes project to lateral horn, a region implicated in control of innate
 odor- related behaviors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And every MBON projects to four neuropils just outside the mushroom body:
 the crepine , the superior medial protocerebrum (SMP) the superior intermediate
 protocerebrum and the superior lateral protocerebrum where input from the
 approach and retreat MBONs is believed to be transformed into motor control.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can classify MBONs according to the behaviour they bias towards.
 In two recent studies it was shown by silencing and activating all 34 MBONs
 that they either promote approach or retreat behaviour (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aso:2014bh,Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, experiments for one such MBON (
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta')$
\end_inset

 have shown bi-directional change in firing rate of the neuron controlled
 by the reinforcement used (appetitive or aversive) .
 Calcium imaging before and after training have shown the response decreases
 compared to the naive response after appetitive learning and increased
 after aversive learning ( Fig.
 2B).
 Furthermore, optogenetic activation of the M4 neurons changed a neutral
 behaviour into avoidance behaviour and blocking the neuron converted a
 naive odour approach into odour retreat in naïve flies (flies that had
 an innate repulsion to an odour without learning).
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
DAs convey reward and punishment signals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dopaminergic neurons (DAs) are the most prevalent modulatory neurons that
 innervate the mushroom bodies.
 There are distinct dopaminergic neurons that provide positive and negative
 value signals.
 The two major clusters where most DANs reside are the PPL and the PAM clusters
 (Fig.
 1c).
 Positive reinforcement are provided by subsets of the approximately 100
 DAs in the PAM cluster (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Burke:2012jt"

\end_inset

).
 They predominately innervate nearby zones in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta,\beta',\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobes.
 Negative reinforcement such as from electric shock or bitter substances
 appears to be conveyed by DANs housed in the PPL cluster.
 Each PPL DAN that innervates the mushroom bodies projects presynaptic terminals
 on the vertical lobes 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha’$
\end_inset

 or heel and surface of the peduncle (David Owald & Scott Waddell – in review).
 The dendrites of MBONs is restricted to few DAN zones.
 For example for the MBON we previously discussed (M4
\begin_inset Formula $\beta'$
\end_inset

) experimental data exists to support that the axons from sugar rewarding
 dopaminergic neurons overlap with the dendrites of the MBON (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
DAs convey reward and punishment signals in different areas of the mushroom
 body 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Distinct DAs convey the effects of sugar and water reward as opposed to
 the same neurons representing subjective value such as in the case of negative
 reinforcing DAs (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Perisse:2013fp"

\end_inset

).
 The sugar and water responsive DAs project to unique zones on the MB lobes,
 thus suggesting that learning-related plasticity is represented at different
 axon terminals along the lobes of the mushroom body.
 It is believed that since DAs reaches a subset of KCs axons, they modify
 KC output synapses onto MBONs in their respective zone.
 Thus water memories and sugar memories are predicted to have unique KC-MBON
 connections that represent them (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Lin:2014ix"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
DA modulated learning changes odour drive to KC-MBON synapses
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A hypothesis of valence learning proposes that learning modifies subsets
 of KC-MBON pathways which in naive flies are balanced (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

).
 Appetitive responding DAs promotes odor approach by depressing odor drive
 to 'avoidance' MBONs and possibly by strenghtening approach pathways.
 Conversely, aversive responding DAs promotes depressing odour drive to
 'approach' MBONs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
DA state control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sugar memory is most robustly expressed in hungry flies and similarly thirst
 promotes the expression of water memory.
 It appears that forming these different memories different zones of the
 MB provides the anatomical requirements in which state control be implemented.
 Interestingly a group of DA neurons that provide the inhibitory constraint
 to the expression of sugar memory (Lin et al, 2014 ) occupy the same zones
 in the heel and peduncle of MB as the MVP2 approach neuron whose activity
 drives approach behaviour.
 Thus it seems likely that the internal state of hunger skews the balance
 of MBON pathways to favour approach.
 It has not been yet shown whether the activation of thirst involves a similar
 layer of control.
 
\end_layout

