\begin_layout Section
Previous modelling attempts of olfactory learning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Previous modelling efforts of the fruit fly's olfactory circuit have mostly
 focused on the neurons implicated in olfactory processing before reaching
 the MBONs, since 3 ladmark papers this year opened the path to modelling
 them 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hige:2015er,Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Aso:2014bh"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, there has been one study that reproduced the valence learning capacity
 of the olfactory circuit (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Wessnitzer:2011dj"

\end_inset

).
 They created a spiking model with dopamine modulated plasticity occurring
 at the synapses between KCs and MBONs and have show that the MBON can learn
 to distinguish between odours of opposite valences.
 In their model, contrary to current evidence dopamine potentiates the weights.
 Their model predicts the fly can also learn an odour mixture discrimination
 task where one half of the odour is paired with a negative reinforcement
 and another half is neutral which has been shown experimentally in the
 bee (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Giurfa:2003dd"

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Putting it all together
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model that was previously discussed serves as a good starting point.
 We have modified the model's dopamine modulated plasticity learning rule
 to explore biologically plausible mechanisms for learning valences of aversive
 and appetitive odours.
 To explore the coding space MBONs form and the competition between MBONs
 which code for approach and those which code for retreat, we modelled two
 MBONs, one that drives each behaviour.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental evidence supports the theory that dopamine dopamine should
 always depress the synapse during plasticity (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Cassenaer:2007go"

\end_inset

).
 However, previous modelling efforts have shown that bi-directional dopamine
 modulation can have computational benefits such as learning more complex
 tasks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fremaux:2010fz"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will develop models for a simple dopamine modulated learning rule always
 leads to depression and for more complex dopamine modulated rule that allow
 for bi-directional control of the synapse and compare which can reconcile
 experimental evidence better.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
2.
 Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiments of the 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 MBON were performed by David Owald at the CNCB and motivated the simulations
 which were created by the author.
 In this first stage we tested dopamine modulated plasticity in the olfactory
 circuit of the fly that can only depress the synapse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Connectivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used experimental data that traces the connectivity between KCs and output
 neurons (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Aso:2014bh"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $M4\beta'$
\end_inset

 neuron receives input from 200 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 lobe and 300 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 lobe.
 The MVP2 neuron receives input from 300 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 lobe and 200 KCs from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha'$
\end_inset

 lobe.
 We do not know the initial synaptic efficacies (weights) between KCs and
 MBONs.
 We make the assumption that the weights between KCs and MBONs have uniform
 random strengths, and have found that by tuning them between 0 nS and 2
 Ns we can reach MBON firing rates of 60 hz which has been show experimentally
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hige:2015er"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
MB Kenyon Cells model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We created a spiking model of the mushroom body valence learning circuit.
 The three main components that required modelling were the Kenyon Cells,
 the MBONs and DAs.
 To simulate an odour we first select randomly 200 neurons that are activated
 when an odour is shown, to ensure 10% sparseness (Andrew Lin et al.
 2014).
 We subsequently generated spike trains which are tuned to known statistics
 of KC spikes (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Turner:2008eo"

\end_inset

).
 KC during spontaneous activity show spiking activity that averages around
 ~0.1 Hz.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When an odour is shown, the 200 KCs fire at 2 Hz with a large concentration
 of spikes occurring in the first 100 ms.
 We generated KC spike trains that fit these properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
MBONs model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 34 MBONs that bias for either approach or retreat.
 As a starting point we modelled two MBONs, one for approach and one for
 retreat (M4 and MVP2).
 Each MBON samples 800 KCs with 200 KCs overlap (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aso:2014bh"

\end_inset

) .
 A recent study peformed who cell recordings of MBONs and observed their
 firing rate is approximately 60 hz before learning.
 Furthermore in contrast to KCs they observed that MBONs are active even
 when no stimulus is shown.
 We used a Linear Integrate and Fire (LIF) model with parameters that were
 taken from a recent modelling paper where whole cell recordings of MBONs
 was performed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hige:2015er"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

