\begin_layout Section
An alternative learning rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have so far used a simple phenomenological learning rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fremaux:2010fz"

\end_inset

.
 However plasticity can be either the results of changes at the presynaptic
 or the postsynaptic terminal.
 It is also unclear whether synaptic depression is sufficient to explain
 behavioural results.
 We will examine a more sophisticated concentration dependent dopamine rule
 that can trigger both potentiation and depression and compare it to our
 initial learning rule.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Implementing the MBON - DA feedback loop
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have begun preliminary work on investigating the MBON - DA feedback loop.
 Recent anatomical work shown that the M4 retreat biasing MBON has axons
 projecting to appetitive DA neurons 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Owald:2015cn"

\end_inset

.
 Our simulaitons predict that the feedback loop would have to be inhibitory
 for stable learning.
 In the case of an excitatory feedback loop, when showing an odour, KCs
 would activate the M4 neuron which in turn would lead to depression, according
 to our learning rule.
 This would make a naive odour become appetitive (Figure 5)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
State dependent memory retrieval 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have modelled the MVP2 neuron which inhibits the M4 neuron.
 However the MVP2 neuron itself is inhibited by the DPM neuron.
 During hunger it is known that the DPM neuron decreases its activity and
 the MVP2 neuron increases creating the conditions for a fly to approach
 a previously neutral odour.
 We would like to model this mechanism together with a second state dependent
 control mechanism of thirst.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Modelling Odour mixtures for experimental validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An unanswered question in the drosophila learning field is how would the
 fruit fly react if it is shown odour mixtures of opposite valences.
 Would a 50% appetitively train odour - 50% aversive mixture be regarded
 as neutral.
 Furthermore would the fly change its behaviour as a function of the concentrati
on ratio?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
A recurrent mushroom body circuit
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first step will be to adding more realistic temporal dynamics in my
 network model.
 Currently, Kenyon Cells spikes are generated by a simple algorithm that
 creates spike trains of a given firing rate and temporal profile.
 However, in the future I would like to model the Kenyon Cells are neurons
 with dynamics that change over time.
 This is because there is evidence that recurrent activity in the mushroom
 bodies involving the APL and DPM neurons and perhaps recurrent activity
 between KCs themselves are critical in stabilizing memories and in retrieving
 them 
